{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17617694","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17617694"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:15:33+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:15:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16479"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16479","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16479"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.39,0.22,0.13,0.13,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9170"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75332"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9170","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9170"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16479"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60841"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4626"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7103"},{"type":"tags","id":"7652"},{"type":"tags","id":"10056"},{"type":"tags","id":"10287"},{"type":"tags","id":"10293"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21776"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21780"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75332","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75332"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EConsider the cellular cascade that occurs during acute cerebral ischaemia. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the sequence of events leading to neuronal damage after decreased ATP production and failure of the sodium-potassium pump?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Membrane depolarisation leading to glutamate release","Direct mitochondrial damage leading to apoptosis","Free radical formation leading to ion pump failure","GABA release leading to neuronal hyperpolarisation","Glutamate release leading to ATP depletion"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe ischaemic cascade in stroke follows a specific sequence of events. After the initial decrease in blood flow, ATP is depleted and ATP-dependent ion pumps fail, and neurons cannot maintain their membrane potential, This leads to \u003Cstrong\u003Emembrane depolarisation and glutamate release\u003C/strong\u003E. Glutamate release leads to activation of calcium channels, which triggers a number of pathways including further glutamate release. This ongoing cycle is referred to as excitotoxicity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirect mitochondrial damage leading to apoptosis\u003C/strong\u003E occurs as a later consequence of the cascade, following calcium overload and oxidative stress, rather than as an immediate sequel to ion pump failure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFree radical formation leading to ion pump failure\u003C/strong\u003E represents an incorrect sequence. Free radicals are generated as a consequence of mitochondrial dysfunction and calcium overload, occurring later in the cascade.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGABA release leading to neuronal hyperpolarisation\u003C/strong\u003E is not part of the primary ischaemic cascade. While GABA is an inhibitory neurotransmitter, its role in acute ischaemia is not significant in the initial phases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGlutamate release leading to ATP depletion\u003C/strong\u003E reverses the actual sequence. ATP depletion is the initiating event that leads to glutamate release, not vice versa.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding this cascade is crucial for developing neuroprotective strategies. The sequence progresses from ATP depletion to sodium-potassium pump dysfunction, membrane depolarisation, glutamate release, calcium influx and subsequent further glutamate release, ultimately causing cell death through various mechanisms including oxidative stress and apoptosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The ischaemic cascade begins with ATP depletion and sodium-potassium pump dysfunction, leading to neuronal membrane depolarisation","Glutamate release follows membrane depolarisation, leading to calcium influx and further glutamate release, referred to as excitotoxicity","Free radical formation and mitochondrial dysfunction are late events in the ischaemic cascade"],"references":["Nishizawa Y. Glutamate release and neuronal damage in ischemia. Life Sci. 2001 Jun 15;69(4):369-81. doi: 10.1016/s0024-3205(01)01142-0. PMID: 11459428.","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022).\u00a0The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60841"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16479"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60841","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60841"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-29T16:29:48+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-29T16:30:40+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9170"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75332"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud